In JavaScript, you can indicate two non-mandatory parameters in a function declaration by assigning a default value to each parameter. Here's an example:

```javascript
function myFunction(param1 = defaultValue1, param2 = defaultValue2) {
  // Function code
}
```

In the above code, `param1` and `param2` are the two non-mandatory parameters in the function `myFunction()`. By assigning default values to the parameters (e.g., `defaultValue1` and `defaultValue2`), you make them optional so that they do not have to be passed when calling the function.

When the function is called without providing any arguments, the parameters will take on their default values. However, if arguments are passed when calling the function, the provided values will override the default values.

In your actual code, you can replace `defaultValue1` and `defaultValue2` with any default values you want, or you can leave them blank (`undefined`) if no default values are desired for the parameters.

